King Abdullah II will fly to Germany for an operation on his spine, Jordanian officials said on Saturday. The 60-year-old monarch has reportedly been suffering from pains in his spine that now require "urgent" intervention. Abdullah II is suffering from a "thoracic herniated disc," according to a statement from Jordan's Royal Hashemite Court. He is expected to arrive in Germany on Sunday, and undergo surgery at a "specialized hospital" in the city of Frankfurt. According to officials, the pain in his spine originated due to his "years of parachuting while serving in the Special Forces." The pain recently increase, however, calling for immediate surgery, the royal court added. King Abdullah II met with Chancellor Olaf Scholz during a recent visit to Berlin in March Following the procedure, Abdullah II will remain in Germany for a week to rest before returning to Jordan. The German government did not immediately comment on the announcement. Abdullah II took the throne in Jordan in 1999 following the death of his father, Hussein. Last year, the king accused his half brother, former Prince Hamzah, of sedition and placed him under house arrest. The incident drew international attention, with Hamzah saying he was being punished for speaking out against corruption. Last week, Hamzah relinquished his royal title in protest over how the country is run. Jordan is a major ally of Western nations in the Middle East. Correction, April 9, 2022: A previous version of this article stated that Jordan's King Abdullah II is flying to Germany on Saturday. It has now been corrected to note the king will travel to Germany on Sunday. DW apologizes for the error. rs/aw (dpa, Reuters)